segments.text: This is Allison Seal, and I'm in Terry Anderson's History Class 374.
I'm interviewing today Mr. Plez Turner, who holds City Council Place 2 on the Bryan City Council.
How long have you lived in Bryan?
Since 1945.
Where did you live before coming to Bryan?
Well, I lived in Bradscott out in the rural area.
Under what conditions did you leave?
Well, I left and went into the service.
And what service?
Army.
Army.
Did you go to World War II and fought?
Yes.
Okay.
When were you elected to the city council?
April 7, 1976.
Okay.
When was your first vote in a public election?
Well, that man that must have been around.
In the late 40s.
In the late 40s?
Okay.
How old were you?
In my early, in my mid-20s.
Where did you vote?
In Bryant?
In Bryant, yes.
Okay, what were, under what conditions were you, was there any kind of discrimination against you in voting?
No, it was normal conditions.
The only thing was you had to have a poll tax.
Uh-huh.
Okay, uh,
In 1964, was there a freedom summer here, or were blacks always allowed to vote as long as they paid the poll tax?
Well, they were always allowed to vote as far as I can remember as long as they paid the poll tax.
Did you go to segregate or desegregate schools?
Segregate schools.
What about your children?
He went to segregate school.
And your grandchildren?
They went to desegregate schools.
When were the schools desegregated in Bryan?
That, I don't remember.
I don't know exactly when it was.
It's been somewhere around 20 something, 20 years ago I'd say.
Okay.
Were the schools equal as in separate but equal before desegregation?
I don't think they were equal.
They were separate and I don't think, I know they were not equal.
Can you describe what you thought the differences were?
Well, the difference that I had was that the black schools did not have the same curriculum as the white schools had.
Since it was totaled with the white schools, it was not totaled with the black schools.
Like what?
Well, when I was going, it said just type it, or it was not totaled.
Uh-huh.
Sciences were taught with labs?
Did they all have labs?
It was a poorly equipped lab.

How do you explain the lack of all due speed in the South to desegregate the schools after Brown versus education, which called for desegregation of separate but equal schools in 1954, but yet schools in Brown that I remember were not desegregated until 1970?
Well, I think it just took
took a while for it to trickle down.
There was a lot of communities that, I mean, after the Supreme Court ruled to desegregate them, it took time for them to put into effect the plans.
Then you kept having court battle after court battle, and people were waiting.
One district was waiting on the other one to see what this court would rule, whether this was legal or not.
And it just took a while for it, before it got down.
What was the feeling among the black community of Bryan after that movement?
I would say the feeling was mixed.
I think the majority of the people held the movement, but some was
a little comprehensive about it, a little worried about what it was going to be like.
Did you feel like that the schools would in time be desegregated, or did you really not have much hope that they would be?
I felt like they would eventually be surrogated, yes.
How has the treatment of Blacks and Bryan changed from the 50s to the 80s, and why do you feel it's changed?
Well, it has been some change.
I guess the main change that I would say would be is that in the early 50s, everything was surrogate.
You had two water fountains.
You had two sets of restrooms.
You had a cafe.
You had two kinds, one for the blacks and one for the whites, you know, things of that nature.
And that has changed, and I think you're being accepted more now than what you were.
Which United States president do you think contributed the most to the civil rights movement?
Well, that's a hard question.
I would have to say Kennedy contributed the most, even though he didn't live very long.
Johnson contributed equally, I'd say, but I think it was between those two presidents.
One started, the other one finished it.
How would you describe President Reagan's devotion to the civil rights on a scale of one to ten?
One.
And why is that?
Well, every move President Reagan has made is to go back to discrimination.
He has cut out the affirmative action program practically, and everything he can do in the legislature would be, it's contrary to the civil rights movement.
What if any acts of discrimination did you experience?
Oh, wait, you mean what I brought up?
Yeah.
Well, like I say, it was that
When we were growing up, it was just two sets of everything.
You could not go to the white schools.
You could not go to the, you know, restaurant.
You had to go around to a side door, a back door.
Or if you go to get a drink, why do they have two fountains?
And thanks to that, nature would discriminate against you.
What were your feelings about the Freedom Rides in 1965 and the race riots and the bus boycotts?
Well, I agreed with the Freedom Rides.
I like the bus boycotts.
I think that they did a lot of good, but for the race routes, I still don't think they did any good.
They might have helped, but I can't see any.
What do you think brought about the change from in the early 60s, the bus boycotts and the freedom rides, you know, from a kind of nonviolent protest to then the black power movement in the late 60s?
Well, I would say Martin Luther King did more for the change than any one man, a black man.
That was what really brought about the change.
But I think the time had just about caught up with it.
See, we were freed over 100 years ago, but still we're not freed.
And then it just kept chipping away and chipping away until we finally just got to the point

What I was speaking of is in the early 1960s with Martin Luther King's nonviolent protest, eventually it changed to what brought about the race riots and things where there was black power movements and it was more a violent protest.
Why do you think that changed?
Well, I think that Martin Luther King, he had enough followers in him.
People respect him enough that when he said nonviolent, they cooperated with him.
Then after he passed along, there was no one else who had that much respect that they could say nonviolent and would have the power to keep it from happening.
What happened in Bryan?
Were there any protests or sit-ins or anything like that?
It might have been some very minor sit-ins, not anything much, though.
Some very minor, yeah, I think it was some minor sit-ins.
Okay.
What organizations such as NAACP and SCLC and SNCC were represented in Bryan?
The NAACP, I think.
Did you belong to any of the groups?
I belonged to NAACP.
What other black leaders besides Martin Luther King do you respect?
Well, I respect Roy Wilkins.
I think he was great.
And I think Benjamin Hooks is a great black leader.
Jesse Jackson is not a great black leader.
What or to whom do you attribute the success of the Civil Rights Movement?
You mean the person?
Or, yeah.
I would have to attribute it to Amanda the King.
When you were elected to the city council, what was the voter turnout during the election, and what percent of white vote and what percent of black vote did you receive?
Well, let's go back.
If we review that first election, it was a good turnout at first because there were several of us running, but it was one black lady, myself, and
Hispanic was in the race.
The Hispanic and I got into a runoff, and the 410, I was re-elected at the end.
I don't have the figures, though.
If I'd have known enough questions, I guess we might have looked it up and got it, but it was very 19.
I don't know.
Okay.
And what about the re-elections when you ran a campaign?
Well, I've had one more runoff with a black lady that was a fairly light turnout.
I think it was about 14% turnout at the end.
But usually, all the races that I've been in, usually it would be about 20% turnout.
When you were on the city council, did you experience any racism, racial jokes, etc.?
No.
Okay.
There have been several terms used to describe blacks, such as colored in the 20s, Negroes in the 50s, and blacks in the 60s.
Why do you feel those terms have changed?
Just people come out with a different word that they want to use.
What is your opinion of these terms?
Do any of them offend you?
Twenty-four percent of the soldiers killed in Vietnam were black, whereas blacks made up only 11 percent of the U.S. society in the 60s.
How would you explain the malaportia?
Do you think that the blacks were drafted over whites?
I don't have any figures on that.
I know that a lot of whites were not drafted.
I've read where a lot of them went to Canada and different places.
But then too, during that time, prosperity was very, it wasn't what it should have been, I don't think.
And a lot of the blacks volunteered for armed services before that.
And a lot of them was caught in the fuck being that Vietnam War thing at the time.
How do you feel black person's chances compared to white person's chances for social mobility are rising in the social status?
I feel that it's considerably less chance.
I think that if the black is one of the elite, the top person, then he can rise.
But if he's an average, like the average white, he has a hard time making the move.
What do you attribute that to?
Well, it's still the same thing, that we want to take care of our own.
As long as you have the white person who is in power who is doing the hiring and the promotion, well, he's going to take care of his own first.
How would you rate the progress of blacks in society today in having attained their civil rights, just starting to almost there or complete?
I'd say they're making progress, but it's
It's a little slow, though.
I don't say they're almost there.
I guess they're about 25% there.
What do you think would bring about complete change, complete progress, complete civil rights?
Time.

Had it not been for the efforts of Truman, Kennedy, and LBJ in attaining civil rights legislation and the Warren Court in upholding the legislation and setting new precedents for civil rights cases, as in Brown v. Board of Education, do you feel blacks today would have the rights they now possess?
Well, I feel that had it not been for them, it would have been other men, other people that would have done the same thing.
I think the time had just come and once
if they happened to be the ones that was in office at that time.
And I feel that after 100 years, I think it would have made some progress.
OK.
I'm talking to Mr. Turner again on desegregation in Bryan School District.
OK, Mr. Turner, you were talking about the differences
in the desegregation as far as busing.
Could you go on and tell me?
Yes.
If you notice that there's only one grade in the black neighborhood, which is the sixth grade, the Kemp College School.
And when we look at that, we see that the white student is only bused out of his neighborhood one year out of the 12 years to come into the minority area.
into the black, predominantly black neighborhood.
But when we reverse that, the black is busted out of his neighborhood.
He's lumping out of the 12 years of high school.
And that's going on right now?
Yes, that's going on right now.
And how long, what do you think will cause a change?
Or do you think there will be a change in that?
Well, on the time there will be a change, the pressure will be put into a change, I think.
Okay, we were also talking about the schools, the black schools in Bryan compared to the white schools, and you were telling me about all the schools that were burnt down.
Could you go through that again and tell me what schools they were and how often, when they were burnt down?
The first school in Bryan was Washington College School.
It was a historical mark.
I don't know whether it's still there, because it was one of the historical schools.
And that school burned down, which, back in the 20s, the blacks that would graduate, they would have on their diploma, brown-colored high school, or something to that effect.
Then the next, that school burned down the next, not very,
They had the junior high school in Brown, which previously was the high school in Brown before the Kemp was built, which was near the high school.
In fact, that school was named Kemp High School until the other high school was built.
And R.C.
Neal was the principal there.
He taught there for quite a few years.
And after his passing, they named that school Neal High School and built a new high school.
And they named it Neal Jr. High School and built a new high school and named it Kemp High School.
And that school also burned down.
Within how many years between the two?
I don't think it was years.
I think it was within months.
I'm not part of that, but the record was shown.
And then there was a third high school that burnt?
No, just the two high schools, just the two schools that burnt.
And what were the feelings among the black community as to how those schools burnt or why they were burnt?
Well, it was a mixed feeling.
They felt that it was, the black community felt that it was some obstinate in there.
arson about white adults or white children?
Well, they didn't, they never did come up with a specific who it was.
It just felt like it was some arson in there.
But I don't think they thought it was children.
They thought it was white adults.
I think we had another school to burn there, if I'm not mistaken.
Did they tear that one down?
If you go back quite a few years ago,
on the side of the cellar.
What was the name of that school there?
What was it called?
See, the Hispanic had school, too.
They were equally surrogated.
And I think that school burned down, too, if I'm not mistaken.

Do you think the reason why they never figured out if it was arson or not is because they didn't really care and they didn't want to point a finger, since it's whites who would be doing the investigating, they didn't want to point fingers at whites?
Well, I'd rather not comment on that, because I really don't know
Okay.
Yes, that school did burn down.
So it's three schools that burned down.
Because the Hispanic used to go to a school.
In their neighborhood?
Yes, it would rather be on Sandy Center and Luckin Street.
Well, a little place around there was a Hispanic school.
Were they segregated as far as fountains and restrooms too?
I don't remember whether it was or whether it was not, but I know they were segregated as far as going to school.
Okay.
When these schools burnt down, around what time did that happen?
During the immigration period.
Did you ever know of any, did you ever travel through the South, or did you ever know of any or hear of any type of
restrictions on blacks in other states?
Well, I traveled through the South, must have been in 57 up until Alabama, and it was pretty bad then for black traveling.
You couldn't, you could not find a hotel hard to see.
It must have been in 64.
It was in 64.
We went to Cincinnati.
We went to Arkansas.
We couldn't find a decent place to live.
Once we spent a night in Arkansas, we couldn't find a decent motel to live in.
We carried Joe to back to Tuskegee at that time.
We stopped at a cafe to eat and they waved us off.
Yeah, that was in 57.
You know, it wasn't a cafe, but it was something like a drive-in, a hot dog place.
And they just keep going.
What other things did you see?
How was the black mood in those towns?
Were they upset or were they just kind of so down?
I don't think they were upset or anything.
It was just...
They had to endure it.
They knew it until they got a chance.
And when the chance came along, man, you know, it was improved.
But back then, in those days, there was nothing they could do.
If they were done with it, they would have been killed.
How did Bryan compare to the other towns?
Did Bryan have as much cruelty toward the blacks, or what do you think?
Not as much as they had that envy of our deep southern states, such as Mississippi, Alabama, and those islands.
Bryan wasn't as bad?
No.
How did the blacks' chances for employment in Bryan compare to those to a white person?
without a college degree or with a college degree?

I say it was slim because it was, blacks had passed exams before, but half of them, there was a fellow named Jim Parker Carroll was a postmaster at that time, and he hired me, and I was the first black carrier hired at the Bryant Post Office.
The black person hired at the Bryant Post Office was a custodian, a janitor.
What year was that?
That's 1955.
As far as for anyone else, what jobs were available to a black man in the 50s and 60s?
Mostly janitorial work.
If you had an education, teaching was about the only thing you could get.
As far as salespersons, there was none.
They were nonexistent for us blacks.
In the banks back there, you had nothing but a custodian, a janitor, an air force, something of that nature.
As far as being a teller or somewhere in the bookkeeping department, something of that nature.
Like the pine trees lining the winding road I've got a name, I've got a name Like the singing bird and the croaking toad I've got a name, I've got a name
And I carry it with me like my daddy did.
But I'm living the dream that he kept here.
Moving me down the highway.
Moving me down the highway.
Moving ahead so life won't pass me by.
Like a north wind whistling down the sky I've got a song I've got a song Like a willful will and the baby's cry I've got a song I've got a song
And I carry it with me and I sing it loud.
If it gets me nowhere, I know they're proud.
Moving me down the highway.
Rolling me down the highway.
Moving to hell till I won't pass the fire.
And I'm gonna go there free Like a fool I am and I'll always be I've got a dream I've got a dream They can change their minds but they can't change me I've got a dream I've got a dream
I know I could share it if you want me to.
If you're going my way, I'll go with you.
Bend me down the highway.
Don't let me down the highway.
One man ahead so life won't pass the by.
Bend me down the highway.
